%%TITLE
Expression of podoplanin and prognosis in oropharyngeal cancer.
%%ABSTRACT
It has been shown that podoplanin expression is associated with carcinoma of the aerodigestive tract. Recent studies indicate that podoplanin may serve as a prognostic biomarker in oral carcinoma. In order to provide evidence on the role of podoplanin in oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma, we evaluated the prognostic impact of podoplanin in these patients. We analyzed formalin-fixed tissue samples from 107 consecutive patients with oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma. HPV typing and immunohistochemical staining for both p16 and podoplanin were performed. Expression of podoplanin was seen in 38.3% of all cases. We found no correlation of the podoplanin scores with either p16 expression or with HPV status. There was no significant correlation of podoplanin expression with the staging variables T, N, M, and tumor grading. Podoplanin expression did neither influence the 5-year overall survival nor the 5-year disease-free survival. Concluding, we could not find a prognostic role of podoplanin expression neither in the HPV-positive cases nor in the HPV-negative cases. It appears that podoplanin is not expressed as often in oropharyngeal cancer compared to oral cancer. We could not show any relation of lymph node metastases and podoplanin expression in this homogenous cohort of tumors.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Subjects and materials
We analyzed tissue specimens from 107 consecutive patients with the diagnosis of squamous cell carcinoma
of the oropharynx. This study was approved by the Ethics Commission of Cologne University’s Faculty of Medicine. We obtained written informed consent from each patient. The assessment of the tumor staging was done using the 2002 American Joint Committee on Cancer staging criteria []. Clinical details and cancer tissue characteristics are pre- sented in Table . Most of the included patients underwent a multimodal treatment approach consisting of surgery and postoperative radio(chemo)therapy. Treatment details have been described in detail previously []. The survival data of some of these patients have also been published previ- ously []. We collected all the follow-up data at visits in 4–6 month intervals at our clinic. Follow-up time was defined as the time from the date of the initial diagnosis until the date of the last visit or the date of death. In this group of patients, the median follow-up time was 22.3 months with a minimum of 0.33 months and a maximum of 131.5 months. We obtained cancer specimens of all cases during the sur- gical procedure. The tissue was fixed in 4 % buffered for- malin and embedded in paraffin using routine procedures. The experiments have all been performed at the University Hospital of Cologne. Initially, all slides were reviewed by the pathologist (U.D.) to select representative areas of vital tumor for further processing and immunohistochemistry. To ensure that representative vital tumor areas were available for immunohistochemistry, we selected only blocks with estimates of at least 70 % tumor cells.
Sample preparation, polymerase chain reaction, and HPV typing
Procession of tissues and PCR procedure were performed as published previously [, ]. In brief, DNA integrity was determined by β-globin gene PCR, and HPV-DNA was detected using nested PCR protocols using degenerated primers A10/A5-A6/A8 and CP62/70-CP65/69a followed by typing of HPV PCR products.
Immunohistochemical staining
Immunohistochemical staining against p16 was appli- cable for formalin-fixed biopsy samples of ninety-nine cases out of this study group. Immunohistochemical stain- ing was performed as published previously by our group
[] using the avidin–biotinylated–peroxidase complex (ABC) method (Chem Mate Detection kit; Dako Cytoma- tion, Carpinteria, CA), primary p16 antibody (Ab-4, clone 16P04 Neo Markers, Fremont, CA), and visualization with 3-amino-9-ethylcarbazol (AEC, Dako Cytomation, Carpin- teria, CA). As a negative control, we used regular periton- sillar squamous cell epithelium. The expression of p16 expression was classified according to criteria that we have published previously in detail [].

For Podoplanin staining, tumor sections (6 µm) were cut from formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded tumor blocks. The sections were mounted on glass slides with silane-treated surface and deparaffinized. We used the avidin–biotin– peroxidase complex technique (ABC-technique) with The Bond ™—maX (A. Menarini diagnostics, Berlin) for stain- ing. The used monoclonal antibody was D2-40 diluted
1:100 (Covance, Princeton, USA). After staining with chro- mogen DAB (A. Menarini diagnostics, Berlin) for 10 min, the sections were counterstained with haematoxylin (A. Menarini diagnostics, Berlin) and mounted using Pertex (Medite, Dietikon).
The scoring classification used was based on a method described by []: both, the rates of positive cells as well as the intensity of the staining were classified from 0 to 3 (0 no Podoplanin expression, 1 weak Podopla- nin expression, 2 moderate Podoplanin expression, and
3 high Podoplanin expression). The sums were added and divided by 2. The final score was allocated to the lower group if the score was not an even number. The slides were classified and allocated to a certain score in a blinded fash- ion by two authors (I.S., S.P.).
Statistical analysis
We used the SPSS Base System (SPSS, version 20, Chi- cago, IL) for statistical analysis. Cross-tabulations and the χ2 test were used to analyze correlations of Podopla- nin expression, p16 expression, and the HPV status. The Kaplan–Meier algorithm was used to estimate the dis- ease-free survival probability and overall survival rates. We used the log-rank test for the univariate analysis of the various variables. A Cox proportional hazards ratio model was used to determine independent predictors of overall survival including factors significant on univariate analysis as covariates. For all mentioned statistical tests, we considered a p value of less than 0.05 statistically significant.
